## Conversation
User: 'when you test conformance client, I think you should decouple the client's
use of shared and have it now rely on its own implementation. This should be
enforced in the linter.' This grew the client PR (andrew/ts-v2-conformance-client)
from 'add a client conformance test' into 'give the client its own digest impl,
enforced by the linter, validated by the conformance test'. It is the payoff of
the corpus: the contract is separated from the implementations, so the client and
server can each own their serialization code.

## What & why
The client computed digests by importing weave.shared.digest (the same code the
server uses). To make client and server INDEPENDENT implementations (so the
server can be extracted to its own package with no client dependency), the client
now has its own copy: weave/trace/digest.py. The conformance corpus is what keeps
the two byte-identical.

## Actions
- New weave/trace/digest.py: bytes_digest, str_digest, compute_object_digest,
  compute_row_digest, compute_table_digest, compute_file_digest. stdlib-only
  (base64/hashlib/json) -- a clean leaf, no weave imports.
- Repointed the only client importers (grep-confirmed: nothing outside weave/trace
  imports weave.shared.digest): weave/trace/weave_client.py (4 fns),
  serialization/op_type.py (str_digest), serialization/serialize.py (bytes_digest).
  ruff --fix re-sorted the imports.
- pyproject.toml: new import-linter contract 'Client must own its serialization
  (not the shared digest impl)' -- source = the client (ROTC) module list,
  forbidden = ['weave.shared.digest'], allow_indirect_imports=true.
- The existing tests/contract/test_conformance_client.py now validates the NEW
  client impl (it goes through weave.publish -> weave.trace.digest).

## Key simplification (verified safe)
The client's compute_object_digest takes NO builtin_object_class. The client only
ever digests already-serialized values (weave_client always calls
compute_object_digest(val) with one arg), and the server's
compute_object_digest(val, None) reduces -- via process_incoming_object_val(val,
None), a pure passthrough -- to str_digest(json.dumps(val, sort_keys=True)). So
the client copy is byte-identical for every input the client produces. The full
client suite (refs/dedup) confirms it.

